fields.text: Did your parents read to you as a child?
Can you move around all day without a recurring injury flaring up?
Are you comfortable holding hands with your significant other(s) in public?
Can you find clothes in your size at a generic clothing store?
Do you think of the police as someone you can call for help?
Have you studied the history and culture of your ethnic ancestors in primary and/or secondary school?
Have you been offered a job with the help of a friend or a family member?
Can you walk home at night without fear of being in danger?
Can you see a doctor when you need to?
Do you commonly relate to people positively portrayed in the media and with whom you share significant aspects of your identity (e.g. race, ethnicity, gender, sexual orientation, ability)?
Are you able to attend events without wondering if the main entrance is accessible to you?
Have professionals of your race, ethnicity, gender, sexual orientation, *and* ability been positively discussed or publicized within the last month?
Is there a national holiday in the country that you live in that honours an aspect/event of your religious/cultural background? (If this doesn't apply to you, skip this question)
Have you always felt like your identity was well-described by categorical boxes on a medical form?
Can you fall asleep easily once you've decided to fall asleep?
Do people always believe you when you say where you're from?
Is the gender on your official documents correct?
Have you always been able to afford at least 2 meals a day?
Can you discuss all aspects of your identity with your family?
Do you know someone who could loan you money in a pinch?
Are you able to attend events without wondering if there's a bathroom you can use?
